@page
@using Helium.Pages.Projects.Shared
@model DescentModelsModel
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = @Model.Card.Title;
}

<div class="container-fluid">
    <partial name="../../Shared/CardHeader.cshtml" for="@Model" />
    <div class="card-body">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-6">
                Using <a href="http://www.123dapp.com/make">Autodesk 123D Make</a>, I converted the
                <a href="http://www.descent2.com/goodies/3dmodels/thinman/descent1/">Class 1 & Class 2</a> drones from the
                <a href="http://www.interplay.com/games/descent.php">Descent</a> video game to physical models.
                <br />
                <partial name="../../Shared/ImageCard.cshtml" ,
                         model='@new Image("/img/hardware-projects/laser-cut/descent-models/green_rob.jpg", "The laser-cut Class 1 drone, assembled.")' />
            </div>
            <div class="col-auto">
                <br />    
                <partial name="../../Shared/ImageCard.cshtml" ,
                         model='@new Image("/img/hardware-projects/laser-cut/descent-models/green_robot.jpg", "The plans for the Class 1 drone being laser-cut.")' />
            </div>
        </div>
        <br />
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-auto">
                <partial name="../../Shared/ImageCard.cshtml" ,
                         model='@new Image("/img/hardware-projects/laser-cut/descent-models/bluerobot_plans.png", "The laser-cut Class 2 drone, designed in Autodesk 123D Make.")' />
            </div>
            <div class="col-auto">
                <partial name="../../Shared/ImageCard.cshtml" ,
                         model='@new Image("/img/hardware-projects/laser-cut/descent-models/blue_rob.jpg", "The laser-cut Class 2 drone, assembled.")' />
            </div>
        </div>
        <br />
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-auto">
                If you'll want to download these models for yourself, be prepared for some complications! First, you'll need to use the
                <a href="http://archive.org/web/web.php">Internet Archive Wayback Machine</a> to acquire the files. After that, <a href="http://brlcad.org/%22">BRL-CAD</a>
                is one of the few programs that can properly convert the unusual 3D model structure into .STL files for import into Autodesk 123D Make.
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>